00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.300
 We're on to our last mini lecture about views,

00:00:02.300 --> 00:00:04.200
 and it's a big one, it's about generic views.

00:00:04.200 --> 00:00:07.040
 It's a really big lecture so that we end up

00:00:07.040 --> 00:00:09.760
 with little tiny views with one line of code.

00:00:09.760 --> 00:00:11.620
 So I've been building up views,

00:00:11.620 --> 00:00:15.240
 and we've talked about inheritance with the templates,

00:00:15.240 --> 00:00:17.540
 and now we're gonna talk about inheritance and views.

00:00:17.540 --> 00:00:20.860
 And we've been inheriting all along with views.

00:00:20.860 --> 00:00:23.460
 So here we are in the views dot py.

00:00:23.460 --> 00:00:28.180
 This whole thing, these particular kinds of views,

00:00:28.180 --> 00:00:30.780
 we define them in views dot py,

00:00:30.780 --> 00:00:34.640
 but they're very informed by the content of model dot py,

00:00:34.640 --> 00:00:39.580
 which means that views are constructed automatically

00:00:39.580 --> 00:00:41.840
 just looking at the data in the models dot py.

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:45.540
 So it's again sort of the logic of don't repeat yourself.

00:00:45.540 --> 00:00:48.260
 If you have a thing in models dot py,

00:00:48.260 --> 00:00:50.580
 you've defined exactly what the fields are,

00:00:50.580 --> 00:00:53.500
 and things like what the help text is for this field,

00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:55.560
 and what the description for the field is,

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:57.460
 that has nothing to do with the database,

00:00:57.460 --> 00:00:59.300
 but it can inform the views.

00:00:59.300 --> 00:01:01.620
 And so it's just a way for,

00:01:01.620 --> 00:01:04.140
 you'll see how it all fits together nicely,

00:01:04.140 --> 00:01:07.900
 but sometimes when we use these super awesome techniques,

00:01:07.900 --> 00:01:09.220
 we end up with a little tiny bit of code,

00:01:09.220 --> 00:01:11.460
 and it's really important to deeply understand

00:01:11.460 --> 00:01:12.980
 that tiny bit of code,

00:01:12.980 --> 00:01:15.540
 because you can sort of just fade away

00:01:15.540 --> 00:01:17.380
 and not realize what's going on,

00:01:17.380 --> 00:01:21.480
 because this code is so cleverly reusing a ton of other code

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:24.120
 and pulling stuff in from other places.

00:01:25.700 --> 00:01:29.140
 So if you go all the way back to we talked about SQL,

00:01:29.140 --> 00:01:32.340
 the four basic operations are put data in a database,

00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:34.000
 get data out of a database,

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:35.860
 delete that data, or update that data.

00:01:35.860 --> 00:01:39.820
 Crud, create, read, update, and delete.

00:01:39.820 --> 00:01:42.600
 And we're gonna build a bunch of things,

00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:45.780
 whether they're ads, add things, or auto things,

00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:47.540
 where we gotta insert an auto,

00:01:47.540 --> 00:01:50.180
 update an auto, delete an auto, list all the autos,

00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:52.740
 insert a cat, delete a cat,

00:01:52.740 --> 00:01:54.780
 list all the cats, update a cat, right?

00:01:54.780 --> 00:01:57.460
 And so we have a bunch of user interfaces

00:01:57.460 --> 00:01:59.900
 that we're gonna build over and over and over again,

00:01:59.900 --> 00:02:01.820
 and as you build your own projects,

00:02:01.820 --> 00:02:04.340
 you'll probably have four or five tables,

00:02:04.340 --> 00:02:07.540
 and then little crud user interfaces for each of the tables.

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:09.260
 And sometimes you make them a little different,

00:02:09.260 --> 00:02:11.760
 and there's pretty stuff on them, and they're customized,

00:02:11.760 --> 00:02:16.760
 but surprisingly often, these things just look the same,

00:02:16.760 --> 00:02:19.100
 and we end up repeating ourselves,

00:02:19.100 --> 00:02:23.560
 which is something we don't wanna do as software developers.

